With tears of pain and pride, I’m blown away by the reaction of the special and beautiful mother of Asher and Yaakov Palei who were murdered in Israel right before Shabbos. 
A group of teenage boys went to be menachem the family and each one of them is expressing a mitzvah that they will start to keep or improve on, in honor of the neshamos of the two beautiful boys. One boy said he’ll put on tefillin every day, another one said he’ll start keeping Shabbos and another announced he’ll improve his kibud horim. 

With warmth and love and appreciation, Mrs Palei thanx them for coming and tells them how much chizuk and comfort they’re bringing the family. 
She then explains to them that her sweet little boys have already finished their mission in this world and are no longer able to learn Torah or grow anymore. 
She told the visiting boys that they’re still young,with their whole lives ahead of them, and that every day they can still continue to learn and grow. 

She shared with them that her younger son Yaakov used to say THANK YOU all the time, for everything. 
She had taught him that he’s a Jewish boy and Jewish people have gratitude for everything and they express that gratitude.
In their home they have a motto: “don’t say Oooof, say Perek Kuf” 

(Mizmor L’Toda)

She suggested to these boys that they start saying Perek Kuf in Tehillim, explaining that it’s not such a difficult things to do, as opposed to some other resolutions or mitzvos that can be harder to commit to. 
Mizmor l’Toda is a Perek of gratitude and she thought it was something they can follow through with. 

She encouraged them to remember that no matter what happens in life, even things that are difficult, painful or uncomfortable, “Always remember that we are Yehudim. That Hashem is with us and everything comes from Him. 
So for everything, we say Thank You.”

Wow wow wow. 
What a stunning kiddush Hashem. 

Starting today I’ll be adopting her motto “Don’t say ooof, say Perek Kuf!”

Who’s joining me? ❤️

I have spent much of my holiday bonding deeply with my eggs, and have learned a great deal from them.

First of all, the egg has strengthened my belief in Hashem. Because it is just impossible for a human being to have created something so magnificent. 
The egg is so versatile and flexible. It can thicken, bind, leaven, glaze and garnish. It can be scrambled, fried, boiled, or poached, depending on what is necessary at the time. 

It can be the main attraction on the plate, or it can blend into the background. 
It is also the most modest kitchen staple. It humbly performs a myriad of culinary functions while barely being noticed. 
The egg says a little...but does a whole lot. 

I have learned from the egg the importance of being flexible in my surroundings, how necessary it is bend over and be accomodating, and how to use all of my abilities, each in the right time and place. 

I have learned that sometimes we need to be the main attraction, but sometimes we need to just blend into the background. 
I have also learned the true meaning of modesty. Modesty is doing from the inside without the need for external acknowledgment. 
And, I have learned the significance of chazal's teaching, to 'say a little but do a lot'. 

The egg has also taught me the importance of going through life with a sense of humor cuz' it's always cracking up. 🙃🙃

And perhaps the most vital lesson of all is that after being cracked, whipped and beaten, the egg still has its sunny side up. 🍳

Seriously, people, this is an eggcellent product. 
I'm not eggzaggerating. 🥚🥚

Rabbi Dee has requested that we post a photo of our families showing our love for Eretz Yisrael and that we continue to shine our light and love in the world. 

So, here’s a photo I took with Yael two weeks ago in our beloved Yerushalayim. 

In the zchus of the three beautiful neshamos of the Dee family, let’s remember that more important than fighting against our external enemies is uniting from within; loving and connecting with our fellow Jewish brothers and sisters. 

Today we mourn; tomorrow we rebuild. 
Together. 
That’s who we are as the Jewish people 🤍

Tonight is Shv’ii Shel Pesach. 

The seventh night / day of Pesach is the anniversary of Krias Yam Suf- the splitting of the sea. It’s an extremely holy day, so let’s take advantage of it!
On Shvii shel Pesach the gates of Heaven are open wide. 
It is a day of abundance. 
A day of God’s revelation. 
A day that He allowed us to see Him clearly in our lives; we saw His love, redemption, and protection. 
On shvii shel Pesach we are told that if we recognize Hashem’s love, if we appreciate His blessings and gifts, and if we open ourselves up to seeing Him in our lives, He will continue blessing us and gifting us with our heart’s deepest desires. 
It is a day of incredible abundance. 

There was so much darkness this week, but the night of Krias Yam suf reminds us that there’s always light in the darkness. 
Hashem can do do ANYTHING for us. 
No matter what sea we’re stuck behind, no matter how deep and frightening it looks, Hashem can go against nature, beyond what’s natural and predictable, and He can split it for us.

On the seventh day of Pesach, let’s thank Hashem for splitting our sea even before He splits it. Let’s manifest our blessings by opening ourselves up and accepting Hashem’s love and by connecting with the Source of all blessing. 

Let’s become vessels to receive Hashem’s shefa and bracha. 

Have a beautiful yom tov filled with light, laughter and love, and may all of your deepest desires be answered with revealed goodness. 

‎באהבה עמוקה
❤️
Yaffa

Today would have been my father’s birthday. 
I’m thinking about the memories that I have of him as a father, which aren’t many, as he was sick for so many years of my life. 

But, I feel blessed to have even the few memories that I do; my younger siblings have no memories at all 😞

My brother expressed the loss he feels in his post this morning, and I’ll share it with you:

“Happy birthday to the man that I miss soo much. To the man who I wish taught me how to live life and navigate through issues. To the man I never really knew because he was sick my whole life. HAPPY BIRTHDAY Abba, words cannot describe how much I miss you !!!!”

Even tho it saddens me that we missed out on having a father, I take solace in knowing we were raised by our Infinite Father, Who loved us and protected us unconditionally. 

And as their oldest sister, I have the privilege of ensuring that my siblings know what an extraordinary man our father truly was 💗

We are independent, confident and proud! We are not victims and we never will be! 💪🏼 🇮🇱
Are we physical beings here for a spiritual experience or are we spiritual beings here for a physical experience?

For some context: On our weekly Lives we’ve been discussing Emunah and Bitachon. 

We’ve been building up the concept of knowing- and feeling- that everything we experience in life is from Hashem, and even more than that, anything that happens is actually the best possible thing for us. 

A question was asked, “what about the painful things we go through?
The physically painful, emotionally painful, disappointing, hurtful things we go through….
We know they’re from  Hashem, but how do we integrate our Emunah and Bitachon into that? 
How do we actually process that pain as something positive?”

So, we spoke about the pain we’re feeling as a physical pain, and that any emotional pain we experience is also coming from a physical being experiencing emotional pain. 

Most people identify themselves as ‘physical beings having a spiritual experience’ 
If that’s true, then WE are experiencing the pain.

But if we know that we’re really ‘spiritual beings having a physical experience’, then while our physical experience is going through pain, discomfort or disappointment right now, that doesn’t mean our spiritual beings, which is who we really are, is in pain. 

In fact, our spiritual selves might even be experiencing pleasure, because what’s happening to us is always good…and the good is not always felt in the body but it’s always felt in the soul. 🤍

On the first day of the Chizuk Mission I spoke about the power of the mind, and the ability to choose which thought or emotion will navigate our lives. 
Then I was challenged by the mind and martial arts master @sunnyblackbelt to strengthen my own mind and use its power alone to break a wooden board with my fist 👊🏼 
After practicing a few times, I did it on the first try! 

It felt exhilarating! Invigorating! Empowering! 

Never underestimate the power of your mind. 

Never underestimate its ability to transcend your limiting beliefs, its ability to turn fear into faith, to choose light over dark, or to change your predetermined destiny.
